<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-08-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-08-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="1489" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1489">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 823.00/107.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-08-05">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 5, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your August 4. The general opinion, corroborated by Billinghurst
                            supporters, is that the ex-President will soon be unconditionally
                            released. His son and brother are now at liberty. Representations have
                            been made at the Foreign Office and among the Diplomatic Corps for
                            concerted action. Application for an audience with the President remains
                            unanswered, but an early interview was promised yesterday at the Foreign
                            Office.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Howard</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>